[Launch4j][1] works on both Windows and Linux/Mac. But if you&#39;re running Linux/Mac, there is a way to embed your jar into a shell script that performs the autolaunch for you, so you have only one runnable file:

`exestub.sh:`

    #!/bin/sh
    MYSELF=`which &quot;$0&quot; 2&gt;/dev/null`
    [ $? -gt  0 -a -f &quot;$0&quot; ] &amp;&amp; MYSELF=&quot;./$0&quot;
    JAVA_OPT=&quot;&quot;
    PROG_OPT=&quot;&quot;
    # Parse options to determine which ones are for Java and which ones are for the Program
    while [ $# -gt 0 ] ; do
    	case $1 in
    		-Xm*) JAVA_OPT=&quot;$JAVA_OPT $1&quot; ;;
    		-D*)  JAVA_OPT=&quot;$JAVA_OPT $1&quot; ;;
    		*)    PROG_OPT=&quot;$PROG_OPT $1&quot; ;;
    	esac
    	shift
    done
    exec java $JAVA_OPT -jar $MYSELF $PROG_OPT

Then you create your runnable file from your jar:

    $ cat exestub.sh myrunnablejar.jar &gt; myrunnable
    $ chmod +x myrunnable

It works the same way launch4j works: because a jar has a [zip format][2], which header is located at the *end* of the file. You can have any header you want (either binary executable or, like here, shell script) and run `java -jar &lt;myexe&gt;`, as `&lt;myexe&gt;` is a valid zip/jar file.


  [1]: http://launch4j.sourceforge.net/
  [2]: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zip_%28file_format%29

